<rss xmlns:taxo="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/taxonomy/" xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" version="2.0">
  <channel>
    <title>One last glimpse of EQ's original magic</title>
    <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Progression&amp;message.id=15758</link>
    <description>&lt;DIV&gt;Despite the usual bickering amongst the now-spoiled EQ community, I applaud the concept of a progression server. Unfortunately, reality is what it is. We might as well call this the Schiavo Server; what we're witnessing here is EQ on life support with people fussing and fighting over mundane topics while the health of the game deteriorates.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Let's face it, folks. Hardly anyone has learned a thing over the last seven years. The players certainly&amp;nbsp;haven't, and that will be demonstrated with the release of Combine. It's going to be one giant race for bragging rights and server-firsts. The disrespect for old-world content which has plagued EQ for years will be magnified tenfold. &lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Some of the devs clearly don't get it either. This quote by Rashere absolutely baffles me:&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;EM&gt;We are not attempting to revert EQ back to its original state.&amp;nbsp; Not only is that a technical impossibility, but the nostalgia people have is due more to it being the first large persistent world that people encountered than any specific gameplay mechanic that has since been changed.&amp;nbsp; That feeling is no more able to be recaptured than the feeling of a first kiss.&lt;/EM&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;It doesn't amaze me that a&amp;nbsp;dev is absolutely clueless. No, what amazes me is that so many players open up wide and swallow this load of crap. They don't even question it. If Rashere says it, hey, it must be so. &lt;STRONG&gt;Bologna&lt;/STRONG&gt;. What Rashere said in the above paragraph translates to, "Your feelings about EQ are comparable to those of a lovesick teenager, and I can't be bothered with them. I'm an all-knowing developer paid by SOE to invent the future, not respect the past."&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;Rashere is flat-out wrong, as is anyone else who insists in a condescending manner that nostalgia is not an integral part of the game. Nostalgia is, was, and always will be something that &lt;EM&gt;can&lt;/EM&gt; be created -- but only if the creator respects its significance. But SOE never has. They don't want to make the game intimate like it once was, they simply want to bleed subscriptions as long as possible. Just as politicians mistakingly "solve" problems by throwing money at them, so goes SOE with their&amp;nbsp;mind-numbing expansions.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;No one -- not Rashere, not hardcore players, not casual players, seems to realize that the magic and mystique of old-world zones&amp;nbsp;&lt;EM&gt;could&lt;/EM&gt; have been preserved. SOE did&amp;nbsp;&lt;EM&gt;not&lt;/EM&gt; need to make the world so ridiculously large so that 90% of the content is empty and depressing. If they had been even slightly creative with the items, plot lines, and content within the existing zones we grew to love so much, there are many who would still be playing (and paying) today.&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;To those who&amp;nbsp;knew, respected, and appreciated&amp;nbsp;the magic that was early EQ, I sincerely hope you rekindle&amp;nbsp;those feelings on the Combine Server. And I sincerely hope I'm wrong when I say it's one last hoorah for a world we'll never see again.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;</description>
    <pubDate>Mon, 29 May 2006 18:29:12 GMT</pubDate>
