      <description>Ummmm...you don't know much about tanking.  Let's say, for example, MT dies, and AoW switches to wrong person.  If that person is a ranger, a monk(did they have a void disc back then, I think so), a rogue, a bard(LoL), or a warrior(tho it was not as good an idea for the warrior), they could use said void disc(for warriors that is fortitude) to buy the right tank time to get controll.  You could not chain discs, but you could use them, and if you are going to die anyway, do it usefully.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Also, I am not exactly wrong about killing AoW, I just don't count those done pre-charm nerf.  here are the details:&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;July 27, 2001 - LoS/SoS kill AoW&lt;br&gt;Aug 2, 2001 - LoS/SoS kill AoW&lt;br&gt;Aug 3, 2001 - Charm and Bind nerf in Kael&lt;br&gt;Dec 2, 2001 - LoS/SoS and FoH/?? kill AoW&lt;br&gt;Dec 4, 2001 - Luclin Launches&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;You could lose AoW after you first beat him, basically due strictly to luck.  AoW was kinda like Reparme, in that, if he wanted you dead, you died.  Beating AoW during Velious/Luclin(post nerf) was all about how many tanks did he decide to kill.  I prefer events that you can win even when the RNG is unkind, as opposed to events where you are at the mercy of luck.  Skill is required in both, but skill should be the deciding factor.</description>
