      <title>Re: One last glimpse of EQ's original magic</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Progression&amp;message.id=16888#M16888</link>
      <description>His point is that instancing is midway between solo gaming and mmorpg's.&amp;nbsp; The more you instance, the more you move along the spectrum away from an mmorpg and towards a solo game.&amp;nbsp; If you carry instancing to it's endpoint, you end up with a solo game.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Our position is that we want to move all the way to the mmorpg end of that spectrum, a persistent, realistic world in which all people interact, and in which all people are able to change the world and hence the gaming experience of other players.&amp;nbsp; We believe that that is what makes mmorpg's worth playing.&amp;nbsp; When you instance, you're no longer playing a 2000 player game, you're playing a 54 person game (or 6, or whatever) because the other players are all effectively cut off from you and cannot influence you, nor you them.&lt;br&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description>
